This episode of showingUP takes you to the front lines of the #COVID #pandemic. For this episode of #ShowingUP join me in listening to Jenna Malone @jmaloneski , a #ski #patroller, #teacher at the American Avalanche Institute, @avyinstitute and physicians assistant who recently spent time caring for covid-19 patients in one of New York's hardest hit areas. This interview took place on @instagram #Live the day after Jenna returned to her home in Utah and was still in quarantine. She talks about what it was like to be on the frontlines of the pandemic before most of the country had experienced it firsthand, why she #volunteered to go there in the first place, and what her daily routine was like while working in the ICU. She also explains why she feels uncomfortable with the outpouring of gratitude that has been directed towards healthcare workers since the start of the pandemic, and shares some of the emotional moments she had with her patients and their families. Lots of my friends are nurses and doctors. Thank you for your service. 
#showup #listen #Subscribe on #iTunes! (Link in bio). #seeyouinthemountains

“I feel like there's a huge opportunity and a blessing in this situation, which is to slow down. To focus on the things that were really important to me and not just the things that I thought were important, but to re-evaluate what is actually important to me. Was I really accomplishing anything and was I fulfilled and happy?” Vanessa Elle Wilde is the Founder and Director of O.Improv, an organization dedicated to helping entrepreneurs with self-confidence, creativity, collaboration and self-expression through Improvisation. node.text:
Week in Review:

1. To Avoid the Next Pandemic, We Need to Stop Factory Farming—Industrial animal agriculture is exacerbating the risks of zoonotic diseases. Are elected officials ready to dismantle the system that got us into this mess?

2. Is Speciesism Driving the Coronavirus Pandemic?—Reluctance to question humans’ exploitation of animals creates a dangerous disconnect in the public’s understanding of COVID-19 and its ongoing risks. Lorelei Plotczyk shares her perspective.

3. I Was a Journalist Who Reported on Captive Animals—Then I Became One—Christina M. Russo reflects on her newfound connection with captive animals. After being damaged during surgery, she understands their plight even more.

4. The Coasts Are Disappearing. We Need to Protect Them for Everyone—Climate change is causing sea levels to rise and coasts to disappear. Can we protect these vital ecosystems for humans and other animals at the same time?

5. Foodies and Factory Farmers Have Formed an Unholy Alliance—Their swipes at fake-meat products—Impossible Burgers, Beyond Meat, and all the rest—are pretty much the same. Robert Paarlberg via @wired

6. The Children Of Smithfield—Last March, while the country grappled with stay-at-home orders, meatpacking plants across the nation quickly became invisible hotspots for the coronavirus. Maira Mendez, a high school administrator in Lincoln, Nebraska, worried her parents might contract coronavirus from their jobs at Smithfield Foods, a massive pork processing plant in the nearby town of Crete. Esther HonigandMary Anne Andrei via @latinousa

To read more, visit the link in our bio ?@sentient_media
